<typeStatus box="[838,994,461,485]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">HOLOTYPE</typeStatus>
], 1 apterous female [
<typeStatus box="[286,434,493,517]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">PARATYPE</typeStatus>
] (
<collectionCode box="[459,535,493,517]" country="Brazil" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/n6nq-8nqh" name="Universidade Federal do Espirito Santo" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">UFES</collectionCode>
); 
<date box="[559,699,493,518]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" value="2009-05-01">
<collectingDate box="[559,699,493,518]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" value="2009-05-01">1 May 2009</collectingDate>
</date>
(
<collectorName box="[719,893,493,517]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">F.F.F. Moreira</collectorName>
): 1 apterous male [
<typeStatus box="[150,298,525,549]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">PARATYPE</typeStatus>
] (
<collectionCode box="[319,395,525,549]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">DZRJ</collectionCode>
)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,277,621,645]" box="[144,277,621,645]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
<emphasis box="[144,277,621,645]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1101,660,812]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
Known only from the short 
<typeStatus box="[460,508,661,685]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">type</typeStatus>
series, collected in a pool approximately 
<quantity box="[968,1037,660,684]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
long, formed along a river branch, and located on the side of dirt road ES-422. Most of the local vegetation was replaced by eucalyptus, and only a few trees surrounded one side of the pool. The specimens were collected in association with hydrophytes of the genus 
<emphasis box="[144,263,788,812]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Eleochares</emphasis>
, which were abundant along the pool margins.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,264,884,908]" box="[144,264,884,908]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
<emphasis box="[144,264,884,908]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1101,923,979]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
<materialsCitation location="State" municipality="The" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Espirito Santo">
<collectingMunicipality box="[144,188,923,947]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">The</collectingMunicipality>
term 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[252,352,923,947]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba">
<emphasis box="[252,352,923,947]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
refers to natives of the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:013287D9FFC7FFAFAB79FBF37B28FED9:8C446014FFC4FFA8A871FC4A789DFC57" box="[608,665,923,947]" municipality="The" name="State" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" stateProvince="Espirito Santo">State</location>
of 
<collectingRegion box="[699,863,923,947]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
, where the 
<typeStatus box="[986,1034,924,948]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">type</typeStatus>
series of the species was collected
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,261,1051,1075]" box="[144,261,1051,1075]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
<emphasis box="[144,261,1051,1075]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1101,1090,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[307,439,1091,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[307,439,1091,1115]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[450,538,1091,1114]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be diagnosed by the body and legs densely covered by long thin setae (
<figureCitation box="[466,588,1122,1146]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[213,280,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,161,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-5@10.[213,1170,161,1531]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Paravelia capixaba sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; male. (B) Head and pronotum; arrow shows circular punctuation; male. (C) Part of thorax; arrow shows circular punctuation on mesoacetabulum; ventrolateral view; male. (D) Fore leg; arrow shows tibial grasping comb; lateral view; male. (E) Proctiger; lateral view; male. (F) Paramere; lateral view; male. (G) Paramere; laterocaudal view; male. (H) Dorsal habitus; female. Scale bar 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5212109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5212109/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Figure 3A</figureCitation>
); antennomere III longer than I; absence of tubercles on thoracic sternites (
<figureCitation box="[502,619,1154,1178]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[213,280,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,161,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-5@10.[213,1170,161,1531]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Paravelia capixaba sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; male. (B) Head and pronotum; arrow shows circular punctuation; male. (C) Part of thorax; arrow shows circular punctuation on mesoacetabulum; ventrolateral view; male. (D) Fore leg; arrow shows tibial grasping comb; lateral view; male. (E) Proctiger; lateral view; male. (F) Paramere; lateral view; male. (G) Paramere; laterocaudal view; male. (H) Dorsal habitus; female. Scale bar 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5212109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5212109/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Figure 3C</figureCitation>
) (the mesoacetabulum is produced on the inner portion of the ventral surface, but not developed into a tubercle like in members of 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus and Polhemus, 1993" authorityName="Polhemus and Polhemus" authorityYear="1993" box="[235,709,1218,1242]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[235,346,1218,1242]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Platyvelia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus JT &amp; Polhemus DA" box="[355,709,1218,1242]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" pagination="391 - 398" refId="ref23038" refString="Polhemus JT, Polhemus DA. 1993. Two new genera for New World Veliinae (Heteroptera: Veliidae). J N Y Entomol Soc. 101 (3): 391 - 398." type="journal article" year="1993">Polhemus and Polhemus, 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
); trochanters and femora without spines, tibiae with a ventral row of black acute spinules throughout their length (
<figureCitation box="[152,275,1282,1306]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[213,280,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,161,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-5@10.[213,1170,161,1531]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Paravelia capixaba sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; male. (B) Head and pronotum; arrow shows circular punctuation; male. (C) Part of thorax; arrow shows circular punctuation on mesoacetabulum; ventrolateral view; male. (D) Fore leg; arrow shows tibial grasping comb; lateral view; male. (E) Proctiger; lateral view; male. (F) Paramere; lateral view; male. (G) Paramere; laterocaudal view; male. (H) Dorsal habitus; female. Scale bar 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5212109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5212109/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Figure 3D</figureCitation>
); male proctiger without central projections, and the shape of the male paramere (
<figureCitation box="[265,410,1314,1338]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="10.[213,280,1564,1586]" captionTargetBox="[213,1170,161,1530]" captionTargetId="figure-5@10.[213,1170,161,1531]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 3. Paravelia capixaba sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; male. (B) Head and pronotum; arrow shows circular punctuation; male. (C) Part of thorax; arrow shows circular punctuation on mesoacetabulum; ventrolateral view; male. (D) Fore leg; arrow shows tibial grasping comb; lateral view; male. (E) Proctiger; lateral view; male. (F) Paramere; lateral view; male. (G) Paramere; laterocaudal view; male. (H) Dorsal habitus; female. Scale bar 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5212109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5212109/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Figure 3F,G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1101,1090,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
Based on original descriptions, 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[536,663,1346,1370]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[536,663,1346,1370]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[669,752,1346,1369]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Drake and Harris, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="Drake and Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capillata">
<emphasis box="[893,1015,1346,1370]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capillata</emphasis>
(Drake and Harris, 1933)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Drake and Harris, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="Drake and Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[355,763,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cognata">
<emphasis box="[355,470,1379,1402]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. cognata</emphasis>
(Drake and Harris, 1933)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1929)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[774,1101,1377,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conata">
<emphasis box="[774,876,1379,1402]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. conata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford HB" box="[890,1093,1377,1401]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" pagination="50 - 59" refId="ref22550" refString="Hungerford HB. 1929. Some new semi-aquatic Hemiptera from South America with a record on stridulatory devices. (Veliidae- Velia). J Kans Entomol Soc. 2 (3): 50 - 59." type="journal article" year="1929">Hungerford, 1929</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hungerford, 1929)" baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[195,540,1409,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis box="[195,309,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. confusa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hungerford HB" box="[325,533,1409,1433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" pagination="50 - 59" refId="ref22550" refString="Hungerford HB. 1929. Some new semi-aquatic Hemiptera from South America with a record on stridulatory devices. (Veliidae- Velia). J Kans Entomol Soc. 2 (3): 50 - 59." type="journal article" year="1929">Hungerford, 1929</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[552,758,1410,1434]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capillata">
<emphasis box="[552,758,1410,1434]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">Paravelia capillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
displays dark brown colouration, sometimes with a blackish pronotum, and legs without bands, which is different from 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[206,335,1473,1497]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[206,335,1473,1497]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[343,428,1474,1497]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Parameres of both species are also different, with only that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[178,304,1505,1529]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capillata">
<emphasis box="[178,304,1505,1529]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capillata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bearing an apical expansion. Representatives of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Drake and Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[876,994,1506,1529]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cognata">
<emphasis box="[876,994,1506,1529]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. cognata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have BL 
<quantity box="[144,231,1537,1561]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
, being distinctly larger than 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[548,676,1537,1561]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[548,676,1537,1561]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[682,769,1538,1561]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and present antennomere III shorter than I.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1101,1090,1689]" lastBlockId="12.[213,1170,166,317]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="2771" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[345,448,1602,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conata">
<emphasis box="[345,448,1602,1625]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. conata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bear a conate projection on the pronotum, not seen elsewhere in the genus, and are almost black, much darker than 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[819,947,1633,1657]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[819,947,1633,1657]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[953,1037,1633,1656]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
They also display two light bands on tibiae, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[695,822,1665,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[695,822,1665,1689]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[828,912,1665,1688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="2770" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
only one band is visible. The male paramere can also be used to distinguish both species, being twisted before the middle and with a basal expansion in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[792,897,199,222]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conata">
<emphasis box="[792,897,199,222]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771">P. conata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Finally, in the case of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hungerford" baseAuthorityYear="1929" box="[213,326,230,254]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Platyvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">
<emphasis box="[213,326,230,254]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771">P. confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, males bear divergent protuberances on last abdominal sternite, which are absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles, 2010" authorityName="Moreira &amp; Nessimian &amp; Rúdio &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2010" box="[320,447,262,286]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Paravelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capixaba" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[320,447,262,286]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771">P. capixaba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[453,539,262,285]" pageId="12" pageNumber="2771" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and male parameres in the former species are wider and shorter.
</paragraph>
